# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ransomware-defense
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] A **backup rotation scheme** is a system of backing up data to computer media (such as tapes) that minimizes, by re-use, the number of media used.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] It determines how and when each piece of removable storage is used for a backup job and how long it is retained after backup data is stored on it.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] Over time, different techniques have evolved to balance data retention and restoration needs with the cost of additional data storage media.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] Such a scheme can become quite complex if it incorporates incremental backups, multiple retention periods, and off-site storage.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] A first in, first out (FIFO) backup scheme saves new or modified files onto the "oldest" media in the set, i.e. the media that contain the oldest and thus least useful previously backed up data.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] Performing a daily backup onto a set of 14 media, the backup depth would be 14 days.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] Each day, the oldest media would be inserted when performing the backup.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] This is the simplest rotation scheme and is usually the first to come to mind.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] This scheme has the advantage that it retains the longest possible tail of daily backups.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] It can be used when archived data is unimportant (or is retained separately from the short-term backup data) and data before the rotation period is irrelevant.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] However, this scheme suffers from the possibility of data loss: suppose, an error is introduced into the data, but the problem is not identified until several generations of backups and revisions have taken place.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] Thus when the error is detected, all the backup files contain the error.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] It would then be useful to have at least one older version of the data, as it would not have the error.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] Grandfather-father-son backup (GFS) is a common rotation scheme for backup media, in which there are three or more backup cycles, such as daily, weekly and monthly.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] The daily backups are rotated on a 3-months basis using a FIFO system as above.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] The weekly backups are similarly rotated on a bi-yearly basis, and the monthly backup on a yearly basis.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] In addition, quarterly, half-yearly, and/or annual backups could also be separately retained.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] Often some of these backups are removed from the site for safekeeping and disaster recovery purposes.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] The Tower of Hanoi rotation method is more complex.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] It is based on the mathematics of the Tower of Hanoi puzzle, using a recursive method to optimize the back-up cycle.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] Every tape corresponds to a disk in the puzzle, and every disk movement to a different peg corresponds with a backup to that tape.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] So the first tape is used every other day (1, 3, 5, 7, 9, ...), the second tape is used every fourth day (2, 6, 10, ...), the third tape is used every eighth day (4, 12, 20, ...).
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] A set of *n* tapes (or other media) will allow backups for 2*n*−1 days before the last set is recycled.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] So, 3 tapes will give 4 days' worth of backups, and on the 4th day *Set C* will be overwritten; 4 tapes will give 8 days, and *Set D* is overwritten on the 9th day; 5 tapes will give 16 days, etc.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] The following tables show which tapes are used on which days of various cycles.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] A disadvantage of the method is that half the backups are overwritten after only two days.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] Many variations are possible, and the concepts are readily extended to disc-based directories containing backups.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] Coverage automatically gets sparser the further back in time one goes, which approximates the likelihood of needing to do restores from past backups.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] And Tower of Hanoi has the huge advantage of freeing implementers from having to deal with managing hourly, daily, weekly, monthly, quarterly or annual management strategies.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] In general, backup set number *set* is used at *seq* = 2*set*−1 + j × 2*set*, *j* = 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, ..., where *seq* is the sequence or serial number of a backup (also the Tower of Hanoi move number).
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] An alternative arrangement is to keep generations distributed across all points in time is by deleting (or overwriting) past generations (except the oldest and the most-recent-*n* generations) when necessary in a weighted-random fashion.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] For each deletion, the weight assigned to each deletable generation corresponds to the probability of it being deleted.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] One acceptable weight is a constant exponent (possibly the square) of the multiplicative inverse of the duration (possibly expressed in the number of days) between the dates of the generation and the generation preceding it.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] Using a larger exponent leads to a more uniform distribution of generations, whereas a smaller exponent leads to a distribution with more recent and fewer older generations.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] This technique probabilistically ensures that past generations are always distributed across all points in time as is desired.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] The weighted random method only has an advantage over a more systematic approach, when backups are irregular or missed.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] This method has many variations and names.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] A set of numbered media is used until the end of the cycle.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] Then the cycle is repeated using media numbered the same as the previous cycle, but incremented by one.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] The lowest numbered tape from the previous cycle is retired and kept permanently.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] Thus one has access to every backup for one cycle and to one backup per cycle before that.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup-rotation-scheme] This method has the advantage of ensuring even media wear, but requires a schedule to be precalculated.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] In information technology, a **backup**, or **data backup** is a copy of computer data taken and stored elsewhere so that it may be used to **restore** the original after a data loss event.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] The verb form, referring to the process of doing so, is "back up", whereas the noun and adjective form is "backup".
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Backups can be used to recover data after its loss from data deletion or corruption, or to recover data from an earlier time.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Backups provide a simple form of IT disaster recovery; however not all backup systems are able to reconstitute a computer system or other complex configuration such as a computer cluster, active directory server, or database server.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] A backup system contains at least one copy of all data considered worth saving.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] The data storage requirements can be large.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] An information repository model may be used to provide structure to this storage.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] There are different types of data storage devices used for copying backups of data that is already in secondary storage onto archive files.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] There are also different ways these devices can be arranged to provide geographic dispersion, data security, and portability.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Data is selected, extracted, and manipulated for storage.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] The process can include methods for dealing with live data, including open files, as well as compression, encryption, and de-duplication.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Additional techniques apply to enterprise client-server backup.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Backup schemes may include dry runs that validate the reliability of the data being backed up.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] There are limitations and human factors involved in any backup scheme.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] A backup strategy requires an information repository, "a secondary storage space for data" that aggregates backups of data "sources".
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] The repository could be as simple as a list of all backup media (DVDs, etc.) and the dates produced, or could include a computerized index, catalog, or relational database.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] The backup data needs to be stored, requiring a backup rotation scheme, which is a system of backing up data to computer media that limits the number of backups of different dates retained separately, by appropriate re-use of the data storage media by overwriting of backups no longer needed.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] The scheme determines how and when each piece of removable storage is used for a backup operation and how long it is retained once it has backup data stored on it.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] The 3-2-1 rule can aid in the backup process.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] It states that there should be at least 3 copies of the data, stored on 2 different types of storage media, and one copy should be kept offsite, in a remote location (this can include cloud storage).
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] 2 or more different media should be used to eliminate data loss due to similar reasons (for example, optical discs may tolerate being underwater while LTO tapes may not, and SSDs cannot fail due to head crashes or damaged spindle motors since they do not have any moving parts, unlike hard drives).
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] An offsite copy protects against fire, theft of physical media (such as tapes or discs) and natural disasters like floods and earthquakes.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Physically protected hard drives are an alternative to an offsite copy, but they have limitations like only being able to resist fire for a limited period of time, so an offsite copy still remains as the ideal choice.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Because there is no perfect storage, many backup experts recommend maintaining a second copy on a local physical device, even if the data is also backed up offsite.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] An unstructured repository may simply be a stack of tapes, DVD-Rs or external HDDs with minimal information about what was backed up and when.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] This method is the easiest to implement, but unlikely to achieve a high level of recoverability as it lacks automation.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] A repository using this backup method contains complete source data copies taken at one or more specific points in time.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Copying system images, this method is frequently used by computer technicians to record known good configurations.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] However, imaging is generally more useful as a way of deploying a standard configuration to many systems rather than as a tool for making ongoing backups of diverse systems.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] An incremental backup stores data changed since a reference point in time.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Duplicate copies of unchanged data are not copied.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Typically a full backup of all files is made once or at infrequent intervals, serving as the reference point for an incremental repository.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Subsequently, a number of incremental backups are made after successive time periods.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Restores begin with the last full backup and then apply the incrementals.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Some backup systems can create a synthetic full backup from a series of incrementals, thus providing the equivalent of frequently doing a full backup.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] When done to modify a single archive file, this speeds restores of recent versions of files.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Continuous Data Protection (CDP) refers to a backup that instantly saves a copy of every change made to the data.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] This allows restoration of data to any point in time and is the most comprehensive and advanced data protection.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Near-CDP backup applications—often marketed as "CDP"—automatically take incremental backups at a specific interval, for example every 15 minutes, one hour, or 24 hours.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] They can therefore only allow restores to an interval boundary.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Near-CDP backup applications use journaling and are typically based on periodic "snapshots", read-only copies of the data frozen at a particular point in time.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Near-CDP (except for Apple Time Machine) intent-logs every change on the host system, often by saving byte or block-level differences rather than file-level differences.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] This backup method differs from simple disk mirroring in that it enables a roll-back of the log and thus a restoration of old images of data.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Near-CDP is more practicable for ordinary personal backup applications, as opposed to *true* CDP, which must be run in conjunction with a virtual machine or equivalent and is therefore generally used in enterprise client-server backups.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Software may create copies of individual files such as written documents, multimedia projects, or user preferences, to prevent failed write events caused by power outages, operating system crashes, or exhausted disk space, from causing data loss.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] A common implementation is an appended ".bak" extension to the file name.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] A Reverse incremental backup method stores a recent archive file "mirror" of the source data and a series of differences between the "mirror" in its current state and its previous states.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] A reverse incremental backup method starts with a non-image full backup.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] After the full backup is performed, the system periodically synchronizes the full backup with the live copy, while storing the data necessary to reconstruct older versions.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] This can either be done using hard links—as Apple Time Machine does, or using binary diffs.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] A differential backup saves only the data that has changed since the last full backup.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] This means a maximum of two backups from the repository are used to restore the data.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] However, as time from the last full backup (and thus the accumulated changes in data) increases, so does the time to perform the differential backup.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Restoring an entire system requires starting from the most recent full backup and then applying just the last differential backup.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Changes in files may be detected through a more recent date/time of last modification file attribute, and/or changes in file size.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Other variations of incremental backup include multi-level incrementals and block-level incrementals that compare parts of files instead of just entire files.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Regardless of the repository model that is used, the data has to be copied onto an archive file data storage medium.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] The medium used is also referred to as the type of backup destination.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Magnetic tape was for a long time the most commonly used medium for bulk data storage, backup, archiving, and interchange.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] It was previously a less expensive option, but this is no longer the case for smaller amounts of data.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Tape is a sequential access medium, so the rate of continuously writing or reading data can be very fast.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] While tape media itself has a low cost per space, tape drives are typically dozens of times as expensive as hard disk drives and optical drives.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Tape media are generally rotated on a schedule so at least one set is off-site in case something should happen to the building where the primary copy of the data lives.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Many tape formats have been proprietary or specific to certain markets like mainframes or a particular brand of personal computer.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] By 2014 LTO had become the primary tape technology.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] The other remaining viable "super" format is the IBM 3592 (also referred to as the TS11xx series).
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] The Oracle StorageTek T10000 was discontinued in 2016.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] The use of hard disk storage has increased over time as it has become progressively cheaper.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Hard disks are usually easy to use, widely available, and can be accessed quickly.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] However, hard disk backups are close-tolerance mechanical devices and may be more easily damaged than tapes, especially while being transported.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Some manufacturers also offer 'ruggedized' portable hard drives, which include a shock-absorbing case around the hard disk, and claim a range of higher drop specifications.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Over a period of years the stability of hard disk backups is shorter than that of tape backups.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] External hard disks can be connected via local interfaces like SCSI, USB, FireWire, or eSATA, or via longer-distance technologies like Ethernet, iSCSI, or Fibre Channel.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Some disk-based backup systems, via Virtual Tape Libraries or otherwise, support data deduplication, which can reduce the amount of disk storage capacity consumed by daily and weekly backup data.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Optical storage uses lasers to store and retrieve data.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Recordable CDs, DVDs, and Blu-ray Discs are commonly used with personal computers and are generally cheap.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] The capacities and speeds of these discs have typically been lower than hard disks or tapes.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Advances in optical media may shrink that gap in the future.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Potential future data losses caused by gradual media degradation can be predicted by measuring the rate of correctable minor data errors, of which consecutively too many increase the risk of uncorrectable sectors.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Support for error scanning varies among optical drive vendors.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Many optical disc formats are WORM type, which makes them useful for archival purposes since the data cannot be changed in any way, including by user error and by malware such as ransomware.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Moreover, optical discs are not vulnerable to head crashes, magnetism, imminent water ingress or power surges; and, a fault of the drive typically just halts the spinning.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Optical media is modular; the storage controller is not tied to media itself like with hard drives or flash storage (→flash memory controller), allowing it to be removed and accessed through a different drive.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] However, recordable media may degrade earlier under long-term exposure to light.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Some optical storage systems allow for cataloged data backups without human contact with the discs, allowing for longer data integrity.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] A French study in 2008 indicated that the lifespan of typically-sold CD-Rs was 2–10 years, but one manufacturer later estimated the longevity of its CD-Rs with a gold-sputtered layer to be as high as 100 years.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Sony's proprietary Optical Disc Archive can in 2016 reach a read rate of 250 MB/s.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Solid-state drives (SSDs) use integrated circuit assemblies to store data.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Flash memory, thumb drives, USB flash drives, CompactFlash, SmartMedia, Memory Sticks, and Secure Digital card devices are relatively expensive for their low capacity, but convenient for backing up relatively low data volumes.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] A solid-state drive does not contain any movable parts, making it less susceptible to physical damage, and can have huge throughput of around 500 Mbit/s up to 6 Gbit/s.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Available SSDs have become more capacious and cheaper.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Flash memory backups are stable for fewer years than hard disk backups.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Remote backup services or cloud backups involve service providers storing data offsite.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] This has been used to protect against events such as fires, floods, or earthquakes which could destroy locally stored backups.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Cloud-based backup (through services like or similar to Google Drive, and Microsoft OneDrive) provides a layer of data protection.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] However, the users must trust the provider to maintain the privacy and integrity of their data, with confidentiality enhanced by the use of encryption.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Because speed and availability are limited by a user's online connection, users with large amounts of data may need to use seed loading and bulk restore.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Various methods can be used to manage backup media, striking a balance between accessibility, security and cost.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] These media management methods are not mutually exclusive and are frequently combined to meet the user's needs.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Using on-line disks for staging data before it is sent to a near-line tape library is a common example.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Online backup storage is typically the most accessible type of data storage, and can begin a restore in milliseconds.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] An internal hard disk or a disk array (maybe connected to SAN) is an example of an online backup.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] This type of storage is convenient and speedy, but is vulnerable to being deleted or overwritten, either by accident, by malevolent action, or in the wake of a data-deleting virus payload.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Nearline storage is typically less accessible and less expensive than online storage, but still useful for backup data storage.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] A mechanical device is usually used to move media units from storage into a drive where the data can be read or written.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Generally it has safety properties similar to on-line storage.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] An example is a tape library with restore times ranging from seconds to a few minutes.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Off-line storage requires some direct action to provide access to the storage media: for example, inserting a tape into a tape drive or plugging in a cable.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Because the data is not accessible via any computer except during limited periods in which they are written or read back, they are largely immune to on-line backup failure modes.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Access time varies depending on whether the media are on-site or off-site.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Backup media may be sent to an off-site vault to protect against a disaster or other site-specific problem.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] The vault can be as simple as a system administrator's home office or as sophisticated as a disaster-hardened, temperature-controlled, high-security bunker with facilities for backup media storage.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] A data replica can be off-site but also on-line (e.g., an off-site RAID mirror).
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] A backup site or disaster recovery center is used to store data that can enable computer systems and networks to be restored and properly configured in the event of a disaster.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Some organisations have their own data recovery centres, while others contract this out to a third-party.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Due to high costs, backing up is rarely considered the preferred method of moving data to a DR site.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] A more typical way would be remote disk mirroring, which keeps the DR data as up to date as possible.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] A backup operation starts with selecting and extracting coherent units of data.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Most data on modern computer systems is stored in discrete units, known as files.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] These files are organized into filesystems.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Deciding what to back up at any given time involves tradeoffs.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] By backing up too much redundant data, the information repository will fill up too quickly.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Backing up an insufficient amount of data can eventually lead to the loss of critical information.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Files that are actively being updated present a challenge to back up.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] One way to back up live data is to temporarily quiesce them (e.g., close all files), take a "snapshot", and then resume live operations.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] At this point the snapshot can be backed up through normal methods.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] A snapshot is an instantaneous function of some filesystems that presents a copy of the filesystem as if it were frozen at a specific point in time, often by a copy-on-write mechanism.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Snapshotting a file while it is being changed results in a corrupted file that is unusable.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] This is also the case across interrelated files, as may be found in a conventional database or in applications such as Microsoft Exchange Server.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] The term fuzzy backup can be used to describe a backup of live data that looks like it ran correctly, but does not represent the state of the data at a single point in time.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Not all information stored on the computer is stored in files.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Accurately recovering a complete system from scratch requires keeping track of this non-file data too.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] It is frequently useful or required to manipulate the data being backed up to optimize the backup process.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] These manipulations can improve backup speed, restore speed, data security, media usage and/or reduced bandwidth requirements.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Out-of-date data can be automatically deleted, but for personal backup applications—as opposed to enterprise client-server backup applications where automated data "grooming" can be customized—the deletion can at most be globally delayed or be disabled.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Various schemes can be employed to shrink the size of the source data to be stored so that it uses less storage space.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Compression is frequently a built-in feature of tape drive hardware.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Redundancy due to backing up similarly configured workstations can be reduced, thus storing just one copy.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] This technique can be applied at the file or raw block level.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] This potentially large reduction is called deduplication.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] It can occur on a server before any data moves to backup media, sometimes referred to as source/client side deduplication.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] This approach also reduces bandwidth required to send backup data to its target media.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] The process can also occur at the target storage device, sometimes referred to as inline or back-end deduplication.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Sometimes backups are duplicated to a second set of storage media.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] This can be done to rearrange the archive files to optimize restore speed, or to have a second copy at a different location or on a different storage medium—as in the disk-to-disk-to-tape capability of Enterprise client-server backup.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] High-capacity removable storage media such as backup tapes present a data security risk if they are lost or stolen.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Encrypting the data on these media can mitigate this problem, however encryption is a CPU intensive process that can slow down backup speeds, and the security of the encrypted backups is only as effective as the security of the key management policy.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] When there are many more computers to be backed up than there are destination storage devices, the ability to use a single storage device with several simultaneous backups can be useful.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] However cramming the scheduled backup window via "multiplexed backup" is only used for tape destinations.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] The process of rearranging the sets of backups in an archive file is known as refactoring.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] For example, if a backup system uses a single tape each day to store the incremental backups for all the protected computers, restoring one of the computers could require many tapes.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Refactoring could be used to consolidate all the backups for a single computer onto a single tape, creating a "synthetic full backup".
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] This is especially useful for backup systems that do incrementals forever style backups.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] Sometimes backups are copied to a staging disk before being copied to tape.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] This process is sometimes referred to as D2D2T, an acronym for Disk-to-disk-to-tape.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] It can be useful if there is a problem matching the speed of the final destination device with the source device, as is frequently faced in network-based backup systems.
[src:ransomware-defense/backup] It can also serve as a centralized location for applying other data manipulation techniques.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] In computing, **data recovery** is a process of retrieving deleted, inaccessible, lost, corrupted, damaged, or overwritten data from secondary storage, removable media or files, when the data stored in them cannot be accessed in a usual way.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] The data is most often salvaged from storage media such as internal or external hard disk drives (HDDs), solid-state drives (SSDs), USB flash drives, magnetic tapes, CDs, DVDs, RAID subsystems, and other electronic devices.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Recovery may be required due to physical damage to the storage devices or logical damage to the file system that prevents it from being mounted by the host operating system (OS).
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Logical failures occur when the hard drive devices are functional but the user or automated-OS cannot retrieve or access data stored on them.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Logical failures can occur due to corruption of the engineering chip, lost partitions, firmware failure, or failures during formatting/re-installation.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Data recovery can be a very simple or technical challenge.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] This is why there are specific software companies specialized in this field that help to get back data on your system.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] The most common data recovery scenarios involve an operating system failure, malfunction of a storage device, logical failure of storage devices, accidental damage or deletion, etc.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] (typically, on a single-drive, single-partition, single-OS system), in which case the ultimate goal is simply to copy all important files from the damaged media to another new drive.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] This can be accomplished using a Live CD, or DVD by booting directly from a ROM or a USB drive instead of the corrupted drive in question.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Many Live CDs or DVDs provide a means to mount the system drive and backup drives or removable media, and to move the files from the system drive to the backup media with a file manager or optical disc authoring software.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Such cases can often be mitigated by disk partitioning and consistently storing valuable data files (or copies of them) on a different partition from the replaceable OS system files.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Another scenario involves a drive-level failure, such as a compromised file system or drive partition, or a hard disk drive failure.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] In any of these cases, the data is not easily read from the media devices.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] If a drive recovery is necessary, the drive itself has typically failed permanently, and the focus is rather on a one-time recovery, salvaging whatever data can be read.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] In a third scenario, files have been accidentally "deleted" from a storage medium by the users.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Typically, the contents of deleted files are not removed immediately from the physical drive; instead, references to them in the directory structure are removed, and thereafter space the deleted data occupy is made available for later data overwriting.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] In the mind of end users, deleted files cannot be discoverable through a standard file manager, but the deleted data still technically exists on the physical drive.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] In the meantime, the original file contents remain, often several disconnected fragments, and may be recoverable if not overwritten by other data files.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] The term "data recovery" is also used in the context of forensic applications or espionage, where data which have been encrypted, hidden, or deleted, rather than damaged, are recovered.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Sometimes data present in the computer gets encrypted or hidden due to reasons like virus attacks which can only be recovered by some computer forensic experts.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] A wide variety of failures can cause physical damage to storage media, which may result from human errors and natural disasters.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] CD-ROMs can have their metallic substrate or dye layer scratched off; hard disks can suffer from a multitude of mechanical failures, such as head crashes, PCB failure, and failed motors; tapes can simply break.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Physical damage to a hard drive, even in cases where a head crash has occurred, does not necessarily mean permanent data loss.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] However, in extreme cases, such as prolonged exposure to moisture and corrosion —like the lost Bitcoin hard drive of James Howells, buried in the Newport landfill for over a decade — recovery is usually impossible.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] In rare cases, forensic techniques such as magnetic force microscopy (MFM) have been explored to detect residual magnetic traces when data holds exceptional value.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Other techniques employed by many professional data recovery companies can typically salvage most, if not all, of the data that had been lost when the failure occurred.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Of course, there are exceptions to this, such as cases where severe damage to the hard drive platters may have occurred.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] However, if the hard drive can be repaired and a full image or clone created, then the logical file structure can be rebuilt in most instances.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Most physical damage cannot be repaired by end users.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] For example, opening a hard disk drive in a normal environment can allow airborne dust to settle on the platter and become caught between the platter and the read/write head.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] During normal operation, read/write heads float 3 to 6 nanometers above the platter surface, and the average dust particles found in a normal environment are typically around 30,000 nanometers in diameter.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] When these dust particles get caught between the read/write heads and the platter, they can cause new head crashes that further damage the platter and thus compromise the recovery process.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Furthermore, end users generally do not have the hardware or technical expertise required to make these repairs.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Consequently, data recovery companies are often employed to salvage important data with the more reputable ones using class 100 dust- and static-free cleanrooms.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Recovering data from physically damaged hardware can involve multiple techniques.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Some damage can be repaired by replacing parts in the hard disk.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] This alone may make the disk usable, but there may still be logical damage.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] A specialized disk-imaging procedure is used to recover every readable bit from the surface.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Once this image is acquired and saved on a reliable medium, the image can be safely analyzed for logical damage and will possibly allow much of the original file system to be reconstructed.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] A common misconception is that a damaged printed circuit board (PCB) may be simply replaced during recovery procedures by an identical PCB from a healthy drive.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] While this may work in rare circumstances on hard disk drives manufactured before 2003, it will not work on newer drives.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Electronics boards of modern drives usually contain drive-specific adaptation data (generally a map of bad sectors and tuning parameters) and other information required to properly access data on the drive.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Replacement boards often need this information to effectively recover all of the data.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] The replacement board may need to be reprogrammed.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Some manufacturers (Seagate, for example) store this information on a serial EEPROM chip, which can be removed and transferred to the replacement board.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Each hard disk drive has what is called a *system area* or *service area*; this portion of the drive, which is not directly accessible to the end user, usually contains drive's firmware and adaptive data that helps the drive operate within normal parameters.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] One function of the system area is to log defective sectors within the drive; essentially telling the drive where it can and cannot write data.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] The sector lists are also stored on various chips attached to the PCB, and they are unique to each hard disk drive.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] If the data on the PCB do not match what is stored on the platter, then the drive will not calibrate properly.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] In most cases the drive heads will click because they are unable to find the data matching what is stored on the PCB.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] The term "logical damage" refers to situations in which the error is not a problem in the hardware and requires software-level solutions.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] In some cases, data on a hard disk drive can be unreadable due to damage to the partition table or file system, or to (intermittent) media errors.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] This type of data recovery can be performed by people without expertise in drive hardware as it requires no special physical equipment or access to platters.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Sometimes data can be recovered using relatively simple methods and tools; more serious cases can require expert intervention, particularly if parts of files are irrecoverable.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Data carving is the recovery of parts of damaged files using knowledge of their structure.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] After data has been physically overwritten on a hard disk drive, it is generally assumed that the previous data are no longer possible to recover.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] In 1996, Peter Gutmann, a computer scientist, presented a paper that suggested overwritten data could be recovered through the use of magnetic force microscopy.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] In 2001, he presented another paper on a similar topic.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] To guard against this type of data recovery, Gutmann and Colin Plumb designed a method of irreversibly scrubbing data, known as the Gutmann method and used by several disk-scrubbing software packages.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Substantial criticism has followed, primarily dealing with the lack of any concrete examples of significant amounts of overwritten data being recovered.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Gutmann's article contains a number of errors and inaccuracies, particularly regarding information about how data is encoded and processed on hard drives.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Although Gutmann's theory may be correct, there is no practical evidence that overwritten data can be recovered, while research has shown to support that overwritten data cannot be recovered.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Solid-state drives (SSD) overwrite data differently from hard disk drives (HDD) which makes at least some of their data easier to recover.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Most SSDs use flash memory to store data in pages and blocks, referenced by logical block addresses (LBA) which are managed by the flash translation layer (FTL).
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] When the FTL modifies a sector it writes the new data to another location and updates the map so the new data appear at the target LBA.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] This leaves the pre-modification data in place, with possibly many generations, and recoverable by data recovery software.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Sometimes, data present in the physical drives (Internal/External Hard disk, Pen Drive, etc.) gets lost, deleted and formatted due to circumstances like virus attack, accidental deletion or accidental use of SHIFT+DELETE.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] In these cases, data recovery software is used to recover/restore the data files.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] In the list of logical failures of hard disks, a logical bad sector is the most common fault leading data not to be readable.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Sometimes it is possible to sidestep error detection even in software, and perhaps with repeated reading and statistical analysis recover at least some of the underlying stored data.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Sometimes prior knowledge of the data stored and the error detection and correction codes can be used to recover even erroneous data.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] However, if the underlying physical drive is degraded badly enough, at least the hardware surrounding the data must be replaced, or it might even be necessary to apply laboratory techniques to the physical recording medium.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Each of the approaches is progressively more expensive, and as such progressively more rarely sought.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Eventually, if the final, physical storage medium has indeed been disturbed badly enough, recovery will not be possible using any means; the information has irreversibly been lost.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Recovery experts do not always need to have physical access to the damaged hardware.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] When the lost data can be recovered by software techniques, they can often perform the recovery using remote access software over the Internet, LAN or other connection to the physical location of the damaged media.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] The process is essentially no different from what the end user could perform by themselves.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Remote recovery requires a stable connection with an adequate bandwidth.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] However, it is not applicable where access to the hardware is required, as in cases of physical damage.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Usually, there are four phases when it comes to successful data recovery, though that can vary depending on the type of data corruption and recovery required.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] The hard drive is repaired in order to get it running in some form, or at least in a state suitable for reading the data from it.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] For example, if heads are bad they need to be changed; if the PCB is faulty then it needs to be fixed or replaced; if the spindle motor is bad the platters and heads should be moved to a new drive.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] When a hard disk drive fails, the importance of getting the data off the drive is the top priority.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] The longer a faulty drive is used, the more likely further data loss is to occur.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Creating an image of the drive will ensure that there is a secondary copy of the data on another device, on which it is safe to perform testing and recovery procedures without harming the source.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] After the drive has been cloned to a new drive, it is suitable to attempt the retrieval of lost data.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] If the drive has failed logically, there are a number of reasons for that.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] (MBR) in order to read the file system's data structure and retrieve stored data.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Data damage can be caused when, for example, a file is written to a sector on the drive that has been damaged.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] This is the most common cause in a failing drive, meaning that data needs to be reconstructed to become readable.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Corrupted documents can be recovered by several software methods or by manually reconstructing the document using a hex editor.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] The Windows operating system can be reinstalled on a computer that is already licensed for it.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] The reinstallation can be done by downloading the operating system or by using a "restore disk" provided by the computer manufacturer.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Eric Lundgren was fined and sentenced to U.S. federal prison in April 2018 for producing 28,000 restore disks and intending to distribute them for about 25 cents each as a convenience to computer repair shops.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] Data recovery cannot always be done on a running system.
[src:ransomware-defense/data-recovery] As a result, a boot disk, live CD, live USB, or any other type of live distro contains a minimal operating system.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Malware poses serious threats to individuals and businesses on the Internet.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] According to Symantec's 2018 Internet Security Threat Report (ISTR), the number of malware variants increased to 669,947,865 in 2017, which is twice as many malware variants as in 2016.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Cybercrime, which includes malware attacks as well as other crimes committed by computer, was predicted to cost the global economy US$6 trillion in 2021, and is increasing at a rate of 15% per year.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Since 2021, malware has been designed to target computer systems that run critical infrastructure such as the electricity distribution network.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The defense strategies against malware differ according to its type, but most can be prevented by installing antivirus software or firewalls, applying regular patches, securing networks, creating backups, and isolating infected systems.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Malware can be designed to evade antivirus software detection algorithms.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The notion of a self-reproducing computer program can be traced back to initial theories about the operation of complex automata.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] John von Neumann showed that in theory a program could reproduce itself.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] This constituted a plausibility result in computability theory.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Fred Cohen experimented with computer viruses and confirmed Neumann's postulate and investigated other properties of malware such as detectability and self-obfuscation using rudimentary encryption.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] His 1987 doctoral dissertation was on the subject of computer viruses.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The combination of cryptographic technology as part of the payload of the virus, exploiting it for attack purposes was initialized and investigated from the mid-1990s, and includes initial ransomware and evasion ideas.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Before Internet access became widespread, viruses spread on personal computers by infecting executable programs or boot sectors of floppy disks.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] By inserting a copy of itself into the machine code instructions in these programs or boot sectors, a virus causes itself to be run whenever the program is run or the disk is booted.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Early computer viruses were written for the Apple II and Mac, but they became more widespread with the dominance of the IBM PC and MS-DOS.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The first IBM PC virus in the wild was a boot sector virus dubbed (c)Brain, created in 1986 by the Farooq Alvi brothers in Pakistan.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Malware distributors would trick the user into booting or running from an infected device or medium.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] For example, a virus could make an infected computer add autorunnable code to any USB stick plugged into it.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Anyone who then attached the stick to another computer set to autorun from USB would in turn become infected, and also pass on the infection in the same way.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Older email software would automatically open HTML email containing potentially malicious JavaScript code.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Users may also execute disguised malicious email attachments.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The *2018 Data Breach Investigations Report* by Verizon, cited by CSO Online, states that emails are the primary method of malware delivery, accounting for 96% of malware delivery around the world.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The first worms, network-borne infectious programs, originated not on personal computers, but on multitasking Unix systems.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The first well-known worm was the Morris worm of 1988, which infected SunOS and VAX BSD systems.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Unlike a virus, this worm did not insert itself into other programs.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Instead, it exploited security holes (vulnerabilities) in network server programs and started itself running as a separate process.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] This same behavior is used by today's worms as well.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] With the rise of the Microsoft Windows platform in the 1990s, and the flexible macros of its applications, it became possible to write infectious code in the macro language of Microsoft Word and similar programs.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] These *macro viruses* infect documents and templates rather than applications (executables), but rely on the fact that macros in a Word document are a form of executable code.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Many early infectious programs, including the Morris Worm, the first internet worm, were written as experiments or pranks.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Today, malware is used by both black hat hackers and governments to steal personal, financial, or business information.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Today, any device that plugs into a USB port – even lights, fans, speakers, toys, or peripherals such as a digital microscope – can be used to spread malware.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Devices can be infected during manufacturing or supply if quality control is inadequate.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Since the rise of widespread broadband Internet access, malicious software has more frequently been designed for profit.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Since 2003, the majority of widespread viruses and worms have been designed to take control of users' computers for illicit purposes.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Infected "zombie computers" can be used to send email spam, to host contraband data such as child pornography, or to engage in distributed denial-of-service attacks as a form of extortion.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Malware is used broadly against government or corporate websites to gather sensitive information, or to disrupt their operation in general.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Further, malware can be used against individuals to gain information such as personal identification numbers or details, bank or credit card numbers, and passwords.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Beyond its use in criminal enterprises, malware has also been deployed as a tool for sabotage, often driven by political objectives.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] A notable example is Stuxnet, which was engineered to interfere with specific industrial control systems.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] In other cases, politically motivated malware attacks have targeted entire networks, causing widespread disruption.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] In 2024, a botnet owner was arrested for engaging in a pay-per-install operation for financial gain.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Malware can be classified in numerous ways, and certain malicious programs may fall into two or more categories simultaneously.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Broadly, software can be categorised into three types: (i) goodware; (ii) grayware and (iii) malware.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] A computer virus is software usually hidden within another seemingly harmless program that can produce copies of itself and insert them into other programs or files, and that usually performs a harmful action (such as destroying data).
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] They have been likened to biological viruses.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] An example of this is a portable execution infection, a technique, usually used to spread malware, that inserts extra data or executable code into PE files.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] A computer virus is software that embeds itself in some other executable software (including the operating system itself) on the target system without the user's knowledge and consent and when it is run, the virus is spread to other executable files.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] A worm is a stand-alone malware software that *actively* transmits itself over a network to infect other computers and can copy itself without infecting files.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] These definitions lead to the observation that a virus requires the user to run an infected software or operating system for the virus to spread, whereas a worm spreads itself.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Once malicious software is installed on a system, it is essential that it stays concealed, to avoid detection.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Software packages known as *rootkits* allow this concealment, by modifying the host's operating system so that the malware is hidden from the user.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Rootkits can prevent a harmful process from being visible in the system's list of processes, or keep its files from being read.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Some types of harmful software contain routines to evade identification or removal attempts, not merely to hide themselves.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] A backdoor is a broad term for a computer program that allows an attacker persistent unauthorised remote access to a victim's machine often without their knowledge.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The attacker typically uses another attack (such as a trojan, worm or virus) to bypass authentication mechanisms usually over an unsecured network such as the Internet to install the backdoor application.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] A backdoor can also be a side effect of a software bug in legitimate software that is exploited by an attacker to gain access to a victim's computer or network.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The idea has often been suggested that computer manufacturers preinstall backdoors on their systems to provide technical support for customers, but this has never been reliably verified.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Backdoors may be installed by Trojan horses, worms, implants, or other methods.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] A Trojan horse misrepresents itself to masquerade as a regular, benign program or utility in order to persuade a victim to install it.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] A Trojan horse usually carries a hidden destructive function that is activated when the application is started.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The term is derived from the Ancient Greek story of the Trojan horse used to invade the city of Troy by stealth.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Trojan horses are generally spread by some form of social engineering, for example, where a user is duped into executing an email attachment disguised to be unsuspicious, (e.g., a routine form to be filled in), or by drive-by download.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] While Trojan horses and backdoors are not easily detectable by themselves, computers may appear to run slower, emit more heat or fan noise due to heavy processor or network usage, as may occur when cryptomining software is installed.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Cryptominers may limit resource usage or only run during idle times in an attempt to evade detection.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Unlike computer viruses and worms, Trojan horses generally do not attempt to inject themselves into other files or otherwise propagate themselves.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Modern Trojans are often disguised within legitimate-looking applications, making them particularly effective at bypassing basic user awareness and simple antivirus measures.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] In spring 2017, Mac users were hit by the new version of Proton Remote Access Trojan (RAT) trained to extract password data from various sources, such as browser auto-fill data, the Mac-OS keychain, and password vaults.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Droppers are a sub-type of Trojans that solely aim to deliver malware upon the system that they infect with the desire to subvert detection through stealth and a light payload.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] It is important not to confuse a dropper with a loader or stager.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] A loader or stager will merely load an extension of the malware (for example a collection of malicious functions through reflective dynamic link library injection) into memory.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The purpose is to keep the initial stage light and undetectable.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] A dropper merely downloads further malware to the system.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Ransomware prevents a user from accessing their files until a ransom is paid.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] There are two variations of ransomware, being crypto ransomware and locker ransomware.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Locker ransomware just locks down a computer system without encrypting its contents, whereas crypto ransomware locks down a system and encrypts its contents.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] For example, programs such as CryptoLocker encrypt files securely, and only decrypt them on payment of a substantial sum of money.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Lock-screens, or screen lockers is a type of "cyber police" ransomware that blocks screens on Windows or Android devices with a false accusation in harvesting illegal content, trying to scare the victims into paying up a fee.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Jisut and SLocker impact Android devices more than other lock-screens, with Jisut making up nearly 60 percent of all Android ransomware detections.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Encryption-based ransomware, like the name suggests, is a type of ransomware that encrypts all files on an infected machine.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] These types of malware then display a pop-up ad informing the user that their files have been encrypted and that they must pay (usually in Bitcoin) to recover them.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Some examples of encryption-based ransomware are CryptoLocker and WannaCry.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Some malware is used to generate money by click fraud, making it appear that the computer user has clicked an advertising link on a site, generating a payment from the advertiser.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] It was estimated in 2012 that about 60 to 70% of all active malware used some kind of click fraud, and 22% of all ad-clicks were fraudulent.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Grayware is any unwanted application or file that can worsen the performance of computers and may cause security risks but which there is insufficient consensus or data to classify them as malware.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Types of grayware typically include spyware, adware, fraudulent dialers, joke programs ("jokeware") and remote access tools.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] For example, at one point, Sony BMG compact discs silently installed a rootkit on purchasers' computers with the intention of preventing illicit copying.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Potentially unwanted programs (PUPs) are applications that would be considered unwanted despite often being intentionally downloaded by the user.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] PUPs include spyware, adware, and fraudulent dialers.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Many security products classify unauthorised key generators as PUPs, although they frequently carry true malware in addition to their ostensible purpose.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] (2012) estimated that as much as 55% of key generators could contain malware and that about 36% malicious key generators were not detected by antivirus software.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Some types of adware turn off anti-malware and virus protection; technical remedies are available.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Programs designed to monitor users' web browsing, display unsolicited advertisements, or redirect affiliate marketing revenues are called spyware.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Spyware programs do not spread like viruses; instead they are generally installed by exploiting security holes.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] They can also be hidden and packaged together with unrelated user-installed software.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The Sony BMG rootkit was intended to prevent illicit copying; but also reported on users' listening habits, and unintentionally created extra security vulnerabilities.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Antivirus software typically uses two techniques to detect malware: (i) static analysis and (ii) dynamic/heuristic analysis.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Static analysis involves studying the software code of a potentially malicious program and producing a signature of that program.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] This information is then used to compare scanned files by an antivirus program.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Because this approach is not useful for malware that has not yet been studied, antivirus software can use dynamic analysis to monitor how the program runs on a computer and block it if it performs unexpected activity.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The aim of any malware is to conceal itself from detection by users or antivirus software.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Detecting potential malware is difficult for two reasons.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The first is that it is difficult to determine if software is malicious.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The second is that malware uses technical measures to make it more difficult to detect it.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] An estimated 33% of malware is not detected by antivirus software.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The most commonly employed anti-detection technique involves encrypting the malware payload in order to prevent antivirus software from recognizing the signature.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Tools such as crypters come with an encrypted blob of malicious code and a decryption stub.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The stub decrypts the blob and loads it into memory.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Because antivirus does not typically scan memory and only scans files on the drive, this allows the malware to evade detection.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Advanced malware has the ability to transform itself into different variations, making it less likely to be detected due to the differences in its signatures.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Other common techniques used to evade detection include, from common to uncommon: (1) evasion of analysis and detection by fingerprinting the environment when executed; (2) confusing automated tools' detection methods.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] This allows malware to avoid detection by technologies such as signature-based antivirus software by changing the server used by the malware; (3) timing-based evasion.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The use of existing binaries to carry out malicious activities is a technique known as LotL, or Living off the Land.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] This reduces the amount of forensic artifacts available to analyze.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Recently these types of attacks have become more frequent with a 432% increase in 2017 and makeup 35% of the attacks in 2018.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Such attacks are not easy to perform but are becoming more prevalent with the help of exploit-kits.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] A vulnerability is a weakness, flaw or software bug in an application, a complete computer, an operating system, or a computer network that is exploited by malware to bypass defences or gain privileges it requires to run.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] For example, TestDisk 6.4 or earlier contained a vulnerability that allowed attackers to inject code into Windows.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] For example, a common method is exploitation of a buffer overrun vulnerability, where software designed to store data in a specified region of memory does not prevent more data than the buffer can accommodate from being supplied.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Malware may provide data that overflows the buffer, with malicious executable code or data after the end; when this payload is accessed it does what the attacker, not the legitimate software, determines.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Malware can exploit recently discovered vulnerabilities before developers have had time to release a suitable patch.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Even when new patches addressing the vulnerability have been released, they may not necessarily be installed immediately, allowing malware to take advantage of systems lacking patches.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Sometimes even applying patches or installing new versions does not automatically uninstall the old versions.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] There are several ways the users can stay informed and protected from security vulnerabilities in software.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Software providers often announce updates that address security issues.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Common vulnerabilities are assigned unique identifiers (CVE IDs) and listed in public databases like the National Vulnerability Database.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Tools like Secunia PSI, free for personal use, can scan a computer for outdated software with known vulnerabilities and attempt to update them.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Firewalls and intrusion prevention systems can monitor the network traffic for suspicious activity that might indicate an attack.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Users and programs can be assigned more privileges than they require, and malware can take advantage of this.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] For example, of 940 Android apps sampled, one third of them asked for more privileges than they required.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Apps targeting the Android platform can be a major source of malware infection but one solution is to use third-party software to detect apps that have been assigned excessive privileges.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Some systems allow all users to make changes to the core components or settings of the system, which is considered over-privileged access today.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] This was the standard operating procedure for early microcomputer and home computer systems, where there was no distinction between an *administrator* or *root*, and a regular user of the system.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] In some systems, non-administrator users are over-privileged by design, in the sense that they are allowed to modify internal structures of the system.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] In some environments, users are over-privileged because they have been inappropriately granted administrator or equivalent status.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] This can be because users tend to demand more privileges than they need, so often end up being assigned unnecessary privileges.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Some systems allow code executed by a user to access all rights of that user, which is known as over-privileged code.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] This was also standard operating procedure for early microcomputer and home computer systems.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Malware, running as over-privileged code, can use this privilege to subvert the system.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Almost all currently popular operating systems, and also many scripting applications allow code too many privileges, usually in the sense that when a user executes code, the system allows that code all rights of that user.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] A credential attack occurs when a user account with administrative privileges is cracked and that account is used to provide malware with appropriate privileges.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Typically, the attack succeeds because the weakest form of account security is used, which is typically a short password that can be cracked using a dictionary or brute force attack.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Using strong passwords and enabling two-factor authentication can reduce this risk.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] With the latter enabled, even if an attacker can crack the password, they cannot use the account without also having the token possessed by the legitimate user of that account.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] It is estimated that approximately 83% of malware infections between January and March 2020 were spread via systems running Windows 10.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] This risk is mitigated by segmenting the networks into different subnetworks and setting up firewalls to block traffic between them.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Anti-malware (sometimes also called antivirus) programs block and remove some or all types of malware.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] For example, Microsoft Security Essentials (for Windows XP, Vista, and Windows 7) and Windows Defender (for Windows 8, 10 and 11) provide real-time protection.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] The Windows Malicious Software Removal Tool removes malicious software from the system.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Additionally, several capable antivirus software programs are available for free download from the Internet (usually restricted to non-commercial use).
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Tests found some free programs to be competitive with commercial ones.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] **Removal:** Anti-malware software programs can be used solely for detection and removal of malware software that has already been installed onto a computer.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] **Sandboxing:** Sandboxing confines applications within a controlled environment, restricting their operations and isolating them from other applications on the host while limiting access to system resources.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Browser sandboxing isolates web processes to prevent malware and exploits, enhancing security.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Any time the operating system accesses a file, the on-access scanner checks if the file is infected or not.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Typically, when an infected file is found, execution is stopped and the file is quarantined to prevent further damage with the intention to prevent irreversible system damage.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Most AVs allow users to override this behaviour.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] This can have a considerable performance impact on the operating system, though the degree of impact is dependent on how many pages it creates in virtual memory.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Sandboxing is a security model that confines applications within a controlled environment, restricting their operations to authorized "safe" actions and isolating them from other applications on the host.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] It also limits access to system resources like memory and the file system to maintain isolation.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Browser sandboxing is a security measure that isolates web browser processes and tabs from the operating system to prevent malicious code from exploiting vulnerabilities.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] It helps protect against malware, zero-day exploits, and unintentional data leaks by trapping potentially harmful code within the sandbox.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] It involves creating separate processes, limiting access to system resources, running web content in isolated processes, monitoring system calls, and memory constraints.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Inter-process communication (IPC) is used for secure communication between processes.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Escaping the sandbox involves targeting vulnerabilities in the sandbox mechanism or the operating system's sandboxing features.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] While sandboxing is not foolproof, it significantly reduces the attack surface of common threats.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Keeping browsers and operating systems updated is crucial to mitigate vulnerabilities.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Website vulnerability scans check the website, detect malware, may note outdated software, and may report known security issues, in order to reduce the risk of the site being compromised.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Structuring a network as a set of smaller networks, and limiting the flow of traffic between them to that known to be legitimate, can hinder the ability of infectious malware to replicate itself across the wider network.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Software-defined networking provides techniques to implement such controls.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] However, malware can still cross the air gap in some situations, not least due to the need to introduce software into the air-gapped network and can damage the availability or integrity of assets thereon.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Stuxnet is an example of malware that is introduced to the target environment via a USB drive, causing damage to processes supported on the environment without the need to exfiltrate data.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] AirHopper, BitWhisper, GSMem and Fansmitter are four techniques introduced by researchers that can leak data from air-gapped computers using electromagnetic, thermal and acoustic emissions.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] Utilizing bibliometric analysis, the study of malware research trends from 2005 to 2015, considering criteria such as impact journals, highly cited articles, research areas, number of publications, keyword frequency, institutions, and authors, revealed an annual growth rate of 34.1%.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] North America led in research output, followed by Asia and Europe.
[src:ransomware-defense/malware] China and India were identified as emerging contributors.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Ransomware attacks are typically carried out using a Trojan disguised as a legitimate file that the user is tricked into downloading or opening when it arrives as an email attachment.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] However, one high-profile example, the WannaCry worm, traveled automatically between computers without user interaction.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Starting as early as 1989 with the first documented ransomware known as the AIDS trojan, the use of ransomware scams grew internationally.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] There were 181.5 million ransomware attacks worldwide in the first six months of 2018, 229% more than the first six months of 2017.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In June 2014, security software company McAfee released data showing that it had collected more than double the number of ransomware samples that quarter than it had in the same quarter the previous year.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] CryptoLocker was particularly successful, procuring an estimated US$3 million before it was taken down by authorities, and CryptoWall was estimated by the US Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) to have accrued over US$18 million by June 2015.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In 2020, the US Internet Crime Complaint Center (IC3) received 2,474 complaints identified as ransomware, with adjusted losses of over $29.1 million.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The losses could exceed this amount, according to the FBI.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Globally, according to Statista, there were about 623 million ransomware attacks in 2021, and 493 million in 2022.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Ransomware payments were estimated at $1.1 billion in 2019, $999m in 2020, a record $1.25bn in 2023, and a sharp drop to $813m in 2024, attributed to non-payment by victims and action by law enforcement.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The concept of file-encrypting ransomware was invented and implemented by Young and Yung at Columbia University and was presented at the 1996 IEEE Security & Privacy conference.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] It is called *cryptoviral extortion* and it was inspired by the fictional facehugger in the movie *Alien*.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Cryptoviral extortion is the following three-round protocol carried out between the attacker and the victim.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] 2. [victim→attacker] To carry out the cryptoviral extortion attack, the malware generates a random symmetric key and encrypts the victim's data with it.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] It uses the public key in the malware to encrypt the symmetric key.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] This is known as hybrid encryption and it results in a small asymmetric ciphertext as well as the symmetric ciphertext of the victim's data.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] It zeroizes the symmetric key and the original plaintext data to prevent recovery.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] It puts up a message to the user that includes the asymmetric ciphertext and how to pay the ransom.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The victim sends the asymmetric ciphertext and e-money to the attacker.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] 3. [attacker→victim] The attacker receives the payment, deciphers the asymmetric ciphertext with the attacker's private key, and sends the symmetric key to the victim.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The victim deciphers the encrypted data with the needed symmetric key thereby completing the cryptovirology attack.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The symmetric key is randomly generated and will not assist other victims.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] At no point is the attacker's private key exposed to victims and the victim need only send a very small ciphertext (the encrypted symmetric-cipher key) to the attacker.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Ransomware attacks are typically carried out using a Trojan, entering a system through, for example, a malicious attachment, an embedded link in a phishing email, or a vulnerability in a network service.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The program then runs a payload, which locks the system in some fashion, or claims to lock the system but does not (e.g., a scareware program).
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Payloads may display a fake warning purportedly by an entity such as a law enforcement agency, falsely claiming that the system has been used for illegal activities, contains content such as pornography and "pirated" media.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Some payloads consist simply of an application designed to lock or restrict the system until payment is made, typically by setting the Windows Shell to itself, or even modifying the master boot record and/or partition table to prevent the operating system from booting until it is repaired.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The most sophisticated payloads encrypt files, with many using strong encryption to encrypt the victim's files in such a way that only the malware author has the needed decryption key.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Payment is virtually always the goal, and the victim is coerced into paying for the ransomware to be removed either by supplying a program that can decrypt the files, or by sending an unlock code that undoes the payload's changes.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] While the attacker may simply take the money without returning the victim's files, it is in the attacker's best interest to perform the decryption as agreed, since victims will stop sending payments if it becomes known that they serve no purpose.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] A key element in making ransomware work for the attacker is a convenient payment system that is hard to trace.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] A range of such payment methods have been used, including wire transfers, premium-rate text messages, pre-paid voucher services such as paysafecard, and the Bitcoin cryptocurrency.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In May 2020, vendor Sophos reported that the global average cost to remediate a ransomware attack (considering downtime, people time, device cost, network cost, lost opportunity and ransom paid) was $761,106.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Ninety-four percent of organizations had their data restored, with 56% of ransomware victims retrieving data from backups, as opposed to 26% when paying the ransom.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The first known malware extortion attack, the "AIDS Trojan" written by Joseph Popp in 1989, had a design failure so severe it was not necessary to pay the extortionist at all.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Its payload hid the files on the hard drive and encrypted only their names, and displayed a message claiming that the user's license to use a certain piece of software had expired.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The user was asked to pay US$189 to "PC Cyborg Corporation" in order to obtain a repair tool even though the decryption key could be extracted from the code of the Trojan.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The Trojan was also known as "PC Cyborg".
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Popp was declared mentally unfit to stand trial for his actions, but he promised to donate the profits from the malware to fund AIDS research.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The idea of abusing anonymous cash systems to safely collect ransom from human kidnapping was introduced in 1992 by Sebastiaan von Solms and David Naccache.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] This electronic money collection method was also proposed for cryptoviral extortion attacks.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In the von Solms-Naccache scenario a newspaper publication was used (since Bitcoin ledgers did not exist at the time the paper was written).
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The notion of using public key cryptography for data kidnapping attacks was introduced in 1996 by Adam L.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Since public key cryptography is used, the virus only contains the *encryption* key.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The attacker keeps the corresponding *private* decryption key private.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Young and Yung's original experimental cryptovirus had the victim send the asymmetric ciphertext to the attacker who deciphers it and returns the symmetric decryption key it contains to the victim for a fee.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Long before electronic money existed Young and Yung proposed that electronic money could be extorted through encryption as well, stating that "the virus writer can effectively hold all of the money ransom until half of it is given to him.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Even if the e-money was previously encrypted by the user, it is of no use to the user if it gets encrypted by a cryptovirus".
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] They referred to these attacks as being "cryptoviral extortion", an overt attack that is part of a larger class of attacks in a field called cryptovirology, which encompasses both overt and covert attacks.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The cryptoviral extortion protocol was inspired by the parasitic relationship between H.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Giger's facehugger and its host in the movie *Alien*.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Examples of extortionate ransomware became prominent in May 2005.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] By mid-2006, Trojans such as Gpcode, TROJ_RANSOM, Archiveus, Krotten, Cryzip, and MayArchive began utilizing more sophisticated RSA encryption schemes, with ever-increasing key-sizes.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Gpcode.AG, which was detected in June 2006, was encrypted with a 660-bit RSA public key.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In June 2008, a variant known as Gpcode.AK was detected.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Using a 1024-bit RSA key, it was believed large enough to be computationally infeasible to break without a concerted distributed effort.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Encrypting ransomware returned to prominence in late 2013 with the propagation of CryptoLocker—using the Bitcoin digital currency platform to collect ransom money.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In December 2013, ZDNet estimated based on Bitcoin transaction information that between 15 October and 18 December, the operators of CryptoLocker had procured about US$27 million from infected users.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In January 2015, it was reported that ransomware-styled attacks have occurred against individual websites via hacking, and through ransomware designed to target Linux-based web servers.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Notably, in 2020, the Ransomware-as-a-service (RaaS) Thanos tool written in C# and made by a Venezualen-French cardiologist Moises Luis Zagala Gonzalez.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] It is one of the first ransomware softwares to use the RIPlace to bypass antivirus techniques.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In 2022, Costa Rica received widespread Conti ransomware attacks affecting government, healthcare and industry.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] This led President Rodrigo Chaves to declare a state of emergency and announce that Costa Rica is "at war" with its ransomware hackers.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In some infections, there is a two-stage payload, common in many malware systems.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The user is tricked into running a script, which downloads the main virus and executes it.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In early versions of the dual-payload system, the script was contained in a Microsoft Office document with an attached VBScript macro, or in a windows scripting facility (WSF) file.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] As detection systems started blocking these first stage payloads, the Microsoft Malware Protection Center identified a trend away toward LNK files with self-contained Microsoft Windows PowerShell scripts.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In 2016, PowerShell was found to be involved in nearly 40% of endpoint security incidents.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Some ransomware strains have used proxies tied to Tor hidden services to connect to their command and control servers, increasing the difficulty of tracing the exact location of the criminals.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Furthermore, dark web vendors have increasingly started to offer the technology as a service, wherein ransomware is sold, ready for deployment on victims' machines, on a subscription basis, similarly to Adobe Creative Cloud or Office 365.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Symantec has classified ransomware to be the most dangerous cyber threat.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In August 2010, Russian authorities arrested nine individuals connected to a ransomware Trojan known as WinLock.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Unlike the previous Gpcode Trojan, WinLock did not use encryption.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Instead, WinLock trivially restricted access to the system by displaying pornographic images and asked users to send a premium-rate SMS (costing around US$10) to receive a code that could be used to unlock their machines.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The scam hit numerous users across Russia and neighbouring countries—reportedly earning the group over US$16 million.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In 2011, a ransomware Trojan surfaced that imitated the Windows Product Activation notice, and informed users that a system's Windows installation had to be re-activated due to "[being a] victim of fraud".
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] An online activation option was offered (like the actual Windows activation process), but was unavailable, requiring the user to call one of six international numbers to input a 6-digit code.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] While the malware claimed that this call would be free, it was routed through a rogue operator in a country with high international phone rates, who placed the call on hold, causing the user to incur large international long-distance charges.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In 2012, Symantec reported spread out of Eastern Europe of ransomware with a lock screen purporting to be law enforcement demanding payment for illegal activity.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In February 2013, a ransomware Trojan based on the Stamp.EK exploit kit surfaced; the malware was distributed via sites hosted on the project hosting services SourceForge and GitHub that claimed to offer "fake nude pics" of celebrities.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In July 2013, an OS X-specific ransomware Trojan surfaced, which displays a web page that accuses the user of downloading pornography.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Unlike its Windows-based counterparts, it does not block the entire computer, but simply exploits the behaviour of the web browser itself to frustrate attempts to close the page through normal means.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] An investigation discovered the incriminating files, and the man was charged with child sexual abuse and possession of child pornography.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The converse of ransomware is a cryptovirology attack invented by Adam L.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Young that threatens to publish stolen information from the victim's computer system rather than deny the victim access to it.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In a leakware attack, malware exfiltrates sensitive host data either to the attacker or alternatively, to remote instances of the malware, and the attacker threatens to publish the victim's data unless a ransom is paid.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The attack was presented at West Point in 2003 and was summarized in the book *Malicious Cryptography* as follows, "The attack differs from the extortion attack in the following way.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In the extortion attack, the victim is denied access to its own valuable information and has to pay to get it back, where in the attack that is presented here the victim retains access to the information but its disclosure is at the discretion of the computer virus".
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The attack is rooted in game theory and was originally dubbed "non-zero sum games and survivable malware".
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The attack can yield monetary gain in cases where the malware acquires access to information that may damage the victim user or organization, e.g., the reputational damage that could result from publishing proof that the attack itself was a success.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Exfiltration attacks are usually targeted, with a curated victim list, and often preliminary surveillance of the victim's systems to find potential data targets and weaknesses.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] With the increased popularity of ransomware on PC platforms, ransomware targeting mobile operating systems has also proliferated.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Typically, mobile ransomware payloads are blockers, as there is little incentive to encrypt data since it can be easily restored via online synchronization.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Mobile ransomware typically targets the Android platform, as it allows applications to be installed from third-party sources.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Different tactics have been used on iOS devices, such as exploiting iCloud accounts and using the Find My iPhone system to lock access to the device.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] On iOS 10.3, Apple patched a bug in the handling of JavaScript pop-up windows in Safari that had been exploited by ransomware websites.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] It recently has been shown that ransomware may also target ARM architectures like those that can be found in various Internet-of-Things (IoT) devices, such as Industrial IoT edge devices.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In August 2019 researchers demonstrated it is possible to infect DSLR cameras with ransomware.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Digital cameras often use Picture Transfer Protocol (PTP) to transfer files.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Researchers found that it was possible to exploit vulnerabilities in the protocol to infect target camera(s) with ransomware (or execute any arbitrary code).
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] This attack was presented at the Defcon security conference in Las Vegas as a proof of concept attack (not as actual armed malware).
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The first attacks were on random users, typically infected through email attachments sent by small groups of criminals, demanding a few hundred dollars in cryptocurrency to unlock files (typically a private individual's photographs and documents) that the ransomware had encrypted.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] As ransomware matured as a business, organised gangs entered the field, advertising on the dark Web for experts, and outsourcing functions.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] This led to improvement in the quality of ransomware and its success.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Rather than random emails, the gangs stole credentials, found vulnerabilities in target networks, and improved the malware to avoid detection by anti-malware scanners.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Ransoms demanded escalated into the much larger sums (millions) that an enterprise would pay to recover its data, rather than what an individual would pay for their documents (hundreds).
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In 2016, a significant uptick in ransomware attacks on hospitals was noted.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] According to the 2017 Internet Security Threat Report from Symantec Corp, ransomware affected not only IT systems but also patient care, clinical operations, and billing.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Online criminals may be motivated by the money available and sense of urgency within the healthcare system.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Ransomware is growing rapidly across the internet users but also for the IoT environment.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The big problem is that millions of dollars are lost by some organizations and industries that have decided to pay, such as the Hollywood Presbyterian Medical Center and the MedStar Health.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] According to Symantec 2019 ISTR report, for the first time since 2013, in 2018 there was an observed decrease in ransomware activity with a drop of 20 percent.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Before 2017, consumers were the preferred victims, but in 2017 this changed dramatically, it moved to the enterprises.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In 2018 this path accelerated with 81 percent infections which represented a 12 percent increase.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The common distribution method today is based on email campaigns.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In late 2019 ransomware group Maze downloaded companies' sensitive files before locking them, and threatened to leak the data publicly if the ransom was not paid; in at least one case they did this.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Many other gangs followed; "leak sites" were created on the dark web where stolen data could be accessed.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Later attacks focussed on the threat to leak data, without necessarily locking it—this negated the protection afforded victims by robust backup procedures.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] As of 2023 there is a risk of hostile governments using ransomware to conceal what is actually intelligence gathering.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The first reported death following a ransomware attack was at a German hospital in October 2020.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] There was a significant increase in ransomware attacks during the 2020 COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Evidence found that the targeted institutions of these attacks included government, finance, and healthcare.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Researchers have contended that several different factors can explain the increase in attacks during this time.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] However, a major factor is that remote work, which became the norm for many industries in 2020, led to the surge in attacks because of the lack of security in comparison to traditional work environments.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Ransomware attacks are estimated to have led to payments totalling $1.1bn in 2019, $999m in 2020, and a record $1.25bn in 2023.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] This decreased to $813m in 2024, with a sharp drop in the second half of the year, according to research firm Chainalysis, attributed to victims refusing to pay, and action by law enforcement.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] However, Chainalysis said that the downward trend in payments was fragile, and ransomware attacks remained prolific.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] A coordinated international operation in February 2024 took down gang LockBit, and gang BlackCat/ALPHV disappeared.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] As of early 2025, the United Kingdom was considering banning schools, the NHS and local councils from making ransomware payments, requiring private companies to report proposed payouts, and requiring mandatory reporting of ransomware attacks.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In 2012, a major ransomware Trojan known as Reveton began to spread.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Based on the Citadel Trojan (which, itself, is based on the Zeus Trojan), its payload displays a warning purportedly from a law enforcement agency claiming that the computer has been used for illegal activities, such as downloading unlicensed software or child pornography.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Due to this behaviour, it is commonly referred to as the "Police Trojan".
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The warning informs the user that to unlock their system, they would have to pay a fine using a voucher from an anonymous prepaid cash service such as Ukash or paysafecard.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] To increase the illusion that the computer is being tracked by law enforcement, the screen also displays the computer's IP address, while some versions display footage from a victim's webcam to give the illusion that the user is being recorded.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Reveton initially began spreading in various European countries in early 2012.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Variants were localized with templates branded with the logos of different law enforcement organizations based on the user's country; for example, variants used in the United Kingdom contained the branding of organizations such as the Metropolitan Police Service and the Police National E-Crime Unit.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Another version contained the logo of the royalty collection society PRS for Music, which specifically accused the user of illegally downloading music.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In a statement warning the public about the malware, the Metropolitan Police clarified that they would never lock a computer in such a way as part of an investigation.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In May 2012, Trend Micro threat researchers discovered templates for variations for the United States and Canada, suggesting that its authors may have been planning to target users in North America.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] By August 2012, a new variant of Reveton began to spread in the United States, claiming to require the payment of a $200 fine to the FBI using a MoneyPak card.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In February 2013, a Russian citizen was arrested in Dubai by Spanish authorities for his connection to a crime ring that had been using Reveton; ten other individuals were arrested on money laundering charges.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In August 2014, Avast Software reported that it had found new variants of Reveton that also distribute password-stealing malware as part of its payload.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Encrypting ransomware reappeared in September 2013 with a Trojan known as *CryptoLocker*, which generated a 2048-bit RSA key pair and uploaded in turn to a command-and-control server, and used to encrypt files using a whitelist of specific file extensions.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The malware threatened to delete the private key if a payment of Bitcoin or a pre-paid cash voucher was not made within 3 days of the infection.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Due to the extremely large key size it uses, analysts and those affected by the Trojan considered CryptoLocker extremely difficult to repair.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Even after the deadline passed, the private key could still be obtained using an online tool, but the price would increase to 10 BTC—which cost approximately US$2300 as of November 2013.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] CryptoLocker was isolated by the seizure of the Gameover ZeuS botnet as part of Operation Tovar, as officially announced by the U.S.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The Department of Justice also publicly issued an indictment against the Russian hacker Evgeniy Bogachev for his alleged involvement in the botnet.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] It was estimated that at least US$3 million was extorted with the malware before the shutdown.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In September 2014, a wave of ransomware Trojans surfaced that first targeted users in Australia, under the names *CryptoWall* and *CryptoLocker* (which is, as with CryptoLocker 2.0, unrelated to the original CryptoLocker).
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Symantec determined that these new variants, which it identified as *CryptoLocker.F*, were again, unrelated to the original CryptoLocker due to differences in their operation.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] A notable victim of the Trojans was the Australian Broadcasting Corporation; live programming on its television news channel ABC News 24 was disrupted for half an hour and shifted to Melbourne studios due to a CryptoWall infection on computers at its Sydney studio.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Another Trojan in this wave, TorrentLocker, initially contained a design flaw comparable to CryptoDefense; it used the same keystream for every infected computer, making the encryption trivial to overcome.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] By late-November 2014, it was estimated that over 9,000 users had been infected by TorrentLocker in Australia alone, trailing only Turkey with 11,700 infections.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Another major ransomware Trojan targeting Windows, CryptoWall, first appeared in 2014.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] One strain of CryptoWall was distributed as part of a malvertising campaign on the Zedo ad network in late-September 2014 that targeted several major websites; the ads redirected to rogue websites that used browser plugin exploits to download the payload.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] A Barracuda Networks researcher also noted that the payload was signed with a digital signature in an effort to appear trustworthy to security software.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] CryptoWall 3.0 used a payload written in JavaScript as part of an email attachment, which downloads executables disguised as JPG images.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] To further evade detection, the malware creates new instances of explorer.exe and svchost.exe to communicate with its servers.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] When encrypting files, the malware also deletes volume shadow copies and installs spyware that steals passwords and Bitcoin wallets.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The FBI reported in June 2015 that nearly 1,000 victims had contacted the bureau's Internet Crime Complaint Center to report CryptoWall infections, and estimated losses of at least $18 million.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The most recent version, CryptoWall 4.0, enhanced its code to avoid antivirus detection, and encrypts not only the data in files but also the file names.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Fusob is a major family of mobile ransomware.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Between April 2015 and March 2016, about 56 percent of accounted mobile ransomware was Fusob.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Like most other pieces of ransomware, it employs scare tactics to extort a hefty sum from the user.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The app acts as if it were a notice from the authorities, demanding the victim to pay a fine from $100 to $200 USD or otherwise face a fictitious criminal charge.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Fusob requests iTunes gift cards for payment, unlike most cryptocurrency-centric ransomware.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In order to infect devices, Fusob masquerades as a pornographic video player.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] When it is installed, it first checks the device's system language.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] If the language is Russian or Eastern-European, Fusob remains dormant.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Otherwise, it locks the device and demands ransom.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] About 40% of victims are in Germany, while the United Kingdom encompasses 14.5% of victims and the US encompasses 11.4%.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Fusob and Small (another family of ransomware) represented over 93% of mobile ransomware between 2015 and 2016.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In May 2017, the WannaCry ransomware attack spread through the Internet, using an exploit vector named EternalBlue, which was allegedly leaked from the U.S.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The ransomware attack, unprecedented in scale, infected more than 230,000 computers in over 150 countries, using 20 different languages to demand money from users using Bitcoin cryptocurrency.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The attackers gave their victims a 7-day deadline from the day their computers got infected, after which the encrypted files would be deleted.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Check Point reported that despite what it believed to be an innovative evolution in ransomware design, it had resulted in relatively-fewer infections than other ransomware active around the same time frame.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] On 27 June 2017, a heavily modified version of Petya was used for a global cyberattack primarily targeting Ukraine (but affecting many countries).
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] This version had been modified to propagate using the same EternalBlue exploit that was used by WannaCry.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Due to another design change, it is also unable to actually unlock a system after the ransom is paid; this led to security analysts speculating that the attack was not meant to generate illicit profit, but to simply cause disruption.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] On 24 October 2017, some users in Russia and Ukraine reported a new ransomware attack, named "Bad Rabbit", which follows a similar pattern to WannaCry and Petya by encrypting the user's file tables and then demanding a Bitcoin payment to decrypt them.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] ESET believed the ransomware to have been distributed by a bogus update to Adobe Flash software.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Among agencies that were affected by the ransomware were: Interfax, Odesa International Airport, Kyiv Metro, and the Ministry of Infrastructure of Ukraine.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] As it used corporate network structures to spread, the ransomware was also discovered in other countries, including Turkey, Germany, Poland, Japan, South Korea, and the United States.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Security experts found that the ransomware did not use the EternalBlue exploit to spread, and a simple method to inoculate an unaffected machine running older Windows versions was found by 24 October 2017.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Further, the sites that had been used to spread the bogus Flash updating have gone offline or removed the problematic files within a few days of its discovery, effectively killing off the spread of Bad Rabbit.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In 2016, a new strain of ransomware emerged that was targeting JBoss servers.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] This strain, named "SamSam", was found to bypass the process of phishing or illicit downloads in favor of exploiting vulnerabilities on weak servers.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The malware uses a Remote Desktop Protocol brute-force attack to guess weak passwords until one is broken.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The virus has been behind attacks on government and healthcare targets, with notable hacks occurring against the town of Farmington, New Mexico, the Colorado Department of Transportation, Davidson County, North Carolina, and most recently, a ransomware attack on the infrastructure of Atlanta.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Mohammad Mehdi Shah Mansouri (born in Qom, Iran in 1991) and Faramarz Shahi Savandi (born in Shiraz, Iran, in 1984) are wanted by the FBI for allegedly launching SamSam ransomware.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The two have allegedly made $6 million from extortion and caused over $30 million in damages using the malware.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] On May 7, 2021, a cyberattack was executed on the US Colonial Pipeline.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The Federal Bureau of Investigation identified DarkSide as the perpetrator of the Colonial Pipeline ransomware attack, perpetrated by malicious code, that led to a voluntary shutdown of the main pipeline supplying 45% of fuel to the East Coast of the United States.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The attack was described as the worst cyberattack to date on the U.S. critical infrastructure.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] DarkSide successfully extorted about 75 Bitcoin (almost US$5 million) from Colonial Pipeline.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] U.S. officials are investigating whether the attack was purely criminal or took place with the involvement of the Russian government or another state sponsor.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In May 2021, the FBI and Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA) issued a joint alert urging the owners and operators of critical infrastructure to take certain steps to reduce their vulnerability to DarkSide ransomware and ransomware in general.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Syskey is a utility that was included with Windows NT-based operating systems to encrypt the user account database, optionally with a password.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The tool has sometimes been effectively used as ransomware during technical support scams—where a caller with remote access to the computer may use the tool to lock the user out of their computer with a password known only to them.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Syskey was removed from later versions of Windows 10 and Windows Server in 2017, due to being obsolete and "known to be used by hackers as part of ransomware scams".
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Ransomware-as-a-service (RaaS) became a notable method after the Russia-based or Russian-speaking group REvil staged operations against several targets, including the Brazil-based JBS S.A. in May 2021, and the US-based Kaseya Limited in July 2021.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Four days later, REvil websites and other infrastructure vanished from the internet.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] If an attack is suspected or detected in its early stages, it takes some time for encryption to take place; immediate removal of the malware (a relatively simple process) before it has completed would stop further damage to data, without salvaging any already lost.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Security experts have suggested precautionary measures for dealing with ransomware.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Using software or other security policies to block known payloads from launching will help to prevent infection, but will not protect against all attacks.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] As such, having a proper backup solution is a critical component to defending against ransomware.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Moreover, if using a NAS or Cloud storage, then the computer should have append-only permission to the destination storage, such that it cannot delete or overwrite previous backups.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] According to comodo, applying two Attack Surface Reduction on OS/Kernel provides a materially-reduced attack surface which results in a heightened security posture.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Installing security updates issued by software vendors can mitigate the vulnerabilities leveraged by certain strains to propagate.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Other measures include cyber hygiene − exercising caution when opening e-mail attachments and links, network segmentation, and keeping critical computers isolated from networks.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Furthermore, to mitigate the spread of ransomware measures of infection control can be applied.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In August 2021, the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA) released a report that provided guidance for how to mitigate ransomware attacks.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] This was due to a significant jump in recent attacks related to ransomware.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] These attacks included aggression against a US pipeline company and a software company, which impacted the downstream customers of MSPs.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Write Once Read Many (WORM) storage, such as many optical disc formats are virtually immune to ransomware since its contents cannot be changed or deleted.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] However data cannot be deleted in any way making it impractical for many storage due to privacy laws and other content laws, the only way is to copy it to a new WORM disk minus the unwanted files, then destroy the original copy.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The healthcare sector has been disproportionately targeted by ransomware attacks, prompting regulatory responses aimed at strengthening requirements for organizations handling sensitive patient data.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In the United States, the 2024 Change Healthcare cyberattack disrupted healthcare payment processing nationwide and affected approximately 100 million individuals, highlighting vulnerabilities in healthcare infrastructure.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] A number of file systems keep snapshots of the data they hold, which can be used to recover the contents of files from a time prior to the ransomware attack in the event the ransomware does not disable it.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] There are a number of tools intended specifically to decrypt files locked by ransomware, although successful recovery may not be possible.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Ransomware encryption that has been cracked by security researchers is typically abandoned for criminal purposes; thus in practice most attacks cannot be reverted by breaking encryption.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The No More Ransom Project is an initiative by the Netherlands' police's National High Tech Crime Unit, Europol's European Cybercrime Centre, Kaspersky Lab and McAfee to help ransomware victims recover their data without paying a ransom.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] They offer a free CryptoSheriff tool to analyze encrypted files and search for decryption tools.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In addition, old copies of files may exist on the disk, which has been previously deleted.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In some cases, these deleted versions may still be recoverable using software designed for that purpose.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] A 2019 ProPublica investigation found the cybersecurity firms Proven Data Recovery and Monstercloud, which advertised ransom-free decryption services, would typically simply pay the ransom and charge the victim a higher price.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] SamSam hackers dealt with Proven Data so frequently that they would recommend the company to victims having technical difficulties making payment.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Other companies like Coveware were more transparent in offering the service of paying the hackers and patching insecure systems.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Many American victims found the ransom amount was too low to meet the United States Department of Justice threshold for federal involvement, but that local police lacked the technical capabilities to help and were often victims themselves.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] A British student, Zain Qaiser, from Barking, London was jailed for more than six years at Kingston upon Thames Crown Court for his ransomware attacks in 2019.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] He is said to have been "the most prolific cyber criminal to be sentenced in the UK".
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] He contacted the Russian controller of one of the most powerful attacks, believed to be the Lurk malware gang, and arranged for a split of his profits.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] He also contacted online criminals from China and the US to move the money.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] For about one and a half years, he posed as a legitimate supplier of online promotions of book advertising on some of the world's most visited legal pornography websites.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Each of the adverts that were promoted on the websites contained the Reveton Ransomware strain of the malicious Angler Exploit Kit (AEK) that seized control of the machine.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Investigators discovered about £700,000 of earnings, although his network may have earned more than £4m.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] He may have hidden some money using cryptocurrencies.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The ransomware would instruct victims to buy GreenDot MoneyPak vouchers and enter the code in the Reveton panel displayed on the screen.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] This money entered a MoneyPak account managed by Qaiser, who would then deposit the voucher payments into the debit card account of his American co-conspirator, Raymond Odigie Uadiale.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Uadiale was a student at Florida International University during 2012 and 2013 and later worked for Microsoft.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Uadiale would convert the money into Liberty Reserve digital currency and deposit it into Qaiser's Liberty Reserve account.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] A breakthrough, in this case, occurred in May 2013 when authorities from several countries seized the Liberty Reserve servers, obtaining access to all its transactions and account history.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Qaiser was running encrypted virtual machines on his Macbook Pro with both Mac and Windows operating systems.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] He could not be tried earlier because he was sectioned (involuntarily committed) under the UK Mental Health Act of 1983 at Goodmayes Hospital where he was found to be using the hospital Wi-Fi to access his advertising sites.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] His lawyer claimed that Qaiser had suffered from mental illness.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Russian police arrested 50 members of the Lurk malware gang in June 2016.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Uadiale, a naturalized US citizen of Nigerian descent, was jailed for 18 months.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] The publication of proof-of-concept attack code is common among academic researchers and vulnerability researchers.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] It teaches the nature of the threat, conveys the gravity of the issues, and enables countermeasures to be devised and put into place.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] However, lawmakers with the support of law-enforcement bodies are contemplating making the creation of ransomware illegal.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] In the state of Maryland, the original draft of HB 340 made it a felony to create ransomware, punishable by up to 10 years in prison.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] A minor in Japan was arrested for creating and distributing ransomware code.
[src:ransomware-defense/ransomware] Australia requires ransomware victims to report their payments to the Australian Signals Directorate in some cases.
